1
00:00:08,635 --> 00:00:10,637
(DOSIMETER CRACKLING FAINTLY)

2
00:00:37,330 --> 00:00:40,041
(MAN READING POEM IN UKRAINIAN
OVER RADIO)

3
00:01:20,123 --> 00:01:22,876
-(DOOR OPENS)
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

4
00:01:33,678 --> 00:01:34,846
(TURNS OFF RADIO)

5
00:01:37,349 --> 00:01:39,100
You work too hard.

6
00:01:40,685 --> 00:01:42,228
Where is everyone?

7
00:01:42,354 --> 00:01:43,772
DMITRI: They refused to come in.

8
00:01:45,148 --> 00:01:46,316
Why?

9
00:01:46,608 --> 00:01:48,401
It's Saturday.

10
00:01:50,820 --> 00:01:51,988
Why did you come in?

11
00:01:52,072 --> 00:01:53,156
DMITRI: I work too hard.

12
00:01:53,573 --> 00:01:54,866
It's boiling in here.

13
00:01:59,704 --> 00:02:01,706
(ALARM BLARING)

14
00:02:07,837 --> 00:02:08,838
(ALARM STOPS)

15
00:02:09,756 --> 00:02:12,217
Eight milliroentgen. A leak?

16
00:02:12,300 --> 00:02:13,301
No.

17
00:02:14,761 --> 00:02:17,097
It would've gone off before.
It's coming from outside.

18
00:02:17,847 --> 00:02:18,932
The Americans?

19
00:02:39,619 --> 00:02:40,829
(MACHINE HUMMING)

20
00:02:45,834 --> 00:02:47,502
(MACHINE WHIRRING)

21
00:02:50,171 --> 00:02:51,673
(PRINTER CLACKING)

22
00:02:59,681 --> 00:03:00,974
Iodine-131.

23
00:03:02,142 --> 00:03:05,395
(SIGHS) It's not military.
It's uranium decay, U-235.

24
00:03:06,146 --> 00:03:07,147
Reactor fuel?

25
00:03:10,275 --> 00:03:13,027
Ignalina. Maybe, uh,
240 kilometers away.

26
00:03:14,195 --> 00:03:15,738
(DIALING)

27
00:03:21,202 --> 00:03:22,370
(LINE RINGS)

28
00:03:22,871 --> 00:03:25,832
Yes, this is Ulana Khomyuk
with the Institute of Nuclear...

29
00:03:25,915 --> 00:03:27,167
(MAN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY OVER PHONE)

30
00:03:27,250 --> 00:03:28,251
Looking for...

31
00:03:33,506 --> 00:03:35,842
-All right, stay calm.
-MAN: Don't tell me to stay calm.

32
00:03:35,925 --> 00:03:37,927
(MAN CONTINUES SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

33
00:03:39,679 --> 00:03:42,182
They're at four. It's not them.

34
00:03:42,849 --> 00:03:43,850
Who's the next closest?

35
00:03:44,392 --> 00:03:46,978
It's Chernobyl, but that's not
possible. They're 400 kilometers away.

36
00:03:47,479 --> 00:03:49,397
That's too far
for eight milliroentgen.

37
00:03:49,481 --> 00:03:50,690
They'd have to be split open.

38
00:03:51,483 --> 00:03:52,734
Maybe they know something.

39
00:03:52,817 --> 00:03:55,028
(PICKS UP RECEIVER, DIALING)

40
00:03:58,323 --> 00:03:59,407
(LINE RINGING)

41
00:04:01,201 --> 00:04:03,036
-Iodine.
-Could it be a waste dump?

42
00:04:03,786 --> 00:04:04,787
No.

43
00:04:05,079 --> 00:04:06,664
We'd be seeing other isotopes.

44
00:04:07,457 --> 00:04:09,042
Nuclear test? Uh...

45
00:04:09,918 --> 00:04:10,960
New kind of bomb?

46
00:04:11,044 --> 00:04:12,962
We'd have heard. That's what
half our people work on here.

47
00:04:15,632 --> 00:04:19,719
Something with the space program
like a satellite or...

48
00:04:22,263 --> 00:04:23,431
No one's answering the phone.

49
00:04:30,396 --> 00:04:32,065
(LINE CONTINUES RINGING)

50
00:04:36,319 --> 00:04:38,488
- (SIREN WAILING)
-(HURRIED CHATTER)

51
00:04:44,744 --> 00:04:46,162
DR. ZINCHENKO:
Get everyone started on an IV.

52
00:04:46,246 --> 00:04:47,247
We don't have enough.

53
00:04:47,330 --> 00:04:49,165
-All the children, then.
-But we don't have enough!

54
00:04:49,249 --> 00:04:50,291
As many as you can!

55
00:04:50,917 --> 00:04:53,419
-Where's the old man?
-He's set up a burn ward in 16.

56
00:04:54,963 --> 00:04:56,756
(BUSY CHATTER)

57
00:05:08,393 --> 00:05:09,602
What are you doing? What is that?

58
00:05:09,769 --> 00:05:12,105
Milk. It's milk.
Much better than water.

59
00:05:12,188 --> 00:05:13,565
No, no, no. Stop. Stop!

60
00:05:13,648 --> 00:05:14,649
DOCTOR: What are you doing?

61
00:05:14,732 --> 00:05:15,984
DR. ZINCHENKO:
These are radiation burns!

62
00:05:16,067 --> 00:05:17,694
Their clothes are contaminated!

63
00:05:18,236 --> 00:05:19,737
Help me!

64
00:05:21,197 --> 00:05:22,198
Get it all off.

65
00:05:22,699 --> 00:05:23,783
(GROANING)

66
00:05:23,866 --> 00:05:25,577
We're taking it down to the basement.

67
00:05:26,160 --> 00:05:27,620
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

68
00:05:28,746 --> 00:05:30,206
He was a firefighter from Chernobyl.

69
00:05:30,290 --> 00:05:31,708
Can you stop pushing, please?

70
00:05:31,958 --> 00:05:33,167
(CLAMORING)

71
00:05:36,004 --> 00:05:37,088
SOLDIER 1: We have our orders!

72
00:05:37,589 --> 00:05:39,549
-Disperse!
-SOLDIER 2: Hey, there! Get him!

73
00:05:42,135 --> 00:05:43,720
WOMAN: Why are you
keeping us out here?

74
00:05:43,803 --> 00:05:44,887
(LYUDMILLA GRUNTS)

75
00:06:38,441 --> 00:06:39,692
(DOOR OPENS)

76
00:06:40,610 --> 00:06:41,611
Professor Legasov?

77
00:06:42,570 --> 00:06:43,613
Oh, no, not yet.

78
00:06:44,197 --> 00:06:46,532
They're finishing up some other
business. It'll be a few more minutes.

79
00:06:46,616 --> 00:06:47,659
Can I get you some tea?

80
00:06:47,742 --> 00:06:49,118
No, I'm fine. Thank you.

81
00:06:49,202 --> 00:06:51,037
Would you care to read
Deputy Chairman Shcherbina's report

82
00:06:51,120 --> 00:06:52,121
while you're waiting?

83
00:06:52,205 --> 00:06:53,373
Certainly. Thank you.

84
00:06:57,835 --> 00:06:59,837
-(DOOR OPENS)
(EXHALES DEEPLY)

85
00:07:00,838 --> 00:07:02,090
(DOOR CLOSES)

86
00:07:51,222 --> 00:07:52,432
(DOOR OPENS)

87
00:07:53,516 --> 00:07:55,101
KREMLIN AIDE: All right, Professor.
They're ready.

88
00:07:56,894 --> 00:07:58,521
Professor Legasov?

89
00:08:24,005 --> 00:08:25,173
GORBACHEV: You have my support.

90
00:08:32,472 --> 00:08:34,390
Thank you all
for your duty to this commission.

91
00:08:34,474 --> 00:08:37,477
We will begin with
Deputy Chairman Shcherbina's briefing,

92
00:08:37,560 --> 00:08:41,022
and then, we will discuss
next steps if necessary.

93
00:08:41,314 --> 00:08:43,191
SHCHERBINA: Thank you,
comrade General Secretary.

94
00:08:43,274 --> 00:08:47,612
I'm pleased to report that
the situation in Chernobyl is stable.

95
00:08:47,695 --> 00:08:50,490
Military and civilian patrols
have secured the region,

96
00:08:50,573 --> 00:08:52,450
and Colonel General Pikalov,

97
00:08:53,159 --> 00:08:55,870
who commands troops specializing
in chemical hazards,

98
00:08:55,953 --> 00:08:57,789
has been dispatched to the plant.

99
00:08:58,122 --> 00:08:59,457
In terms of radiation,

100
00:08:59,540 --> 00:09:03,753
plant director Bryukhanov
reports no more than 3.6 roentgen.

101
00:09:04,170 --> 00:09:06,714
I'm told it's the equivalent
of a chest X-ray.

102
00:09:06,798 --> 00:09:09,342
So if you're overdue for a check-up...

103
00:09:09,717 --> 00:09:11,803
-And foreign press?
-SHCHERBINA: Totally unaware.

104
00:09:12,512 --> 00:09:14,889
KGB First Deputy Chairman
Charkov assures me

105
00:09:14,972 --> 00:09:17,642
that we have successfully
protected our security interests.

106
00:09:18,226 --> 00:09:20,311
GORBACHEV: Good. Very good.

107
00:09:20,728 --> 00:09:23,064
Well, it seems like
it's well in hand, so...

108
00:09:24,524 --> 00:09:26,984
If there's nothing else,
meeting adjourned.

109
00:09:28,277 --> 00:09:29,278
No!

110
00:09:32,240 --> 00:09:33,241
Pardon me?

111
00:09:34,283 --> 00:09:35,952
Uh, we can't adjourn.

112
00:09:36,577 --> 00:09:38,913
This is Professor Legasov
of the Kurchatov Institute.

113
00:09:39,330 --> 00:09:40,915
Professor, if you have any concerns,

114
00:09:40,998 --> 00:09:42,792
feel free to address them
with me later.

115
00:09:42,875 --> 00:09:45,795
I can't. I am sorry. I'm so sorry.

116
00:09:46,754 --> 00:09:50,383
Page three, the section on casualties.
Uh...

117
00:09:51,342 --> 00:09:54,262
"A fireman was severely
burned on his hand

118
00:09:54,345 --> 00:09:56,681
"by a chunk of smooth, black mineral

119
00:09:56,764 --> 00:09:59,267
"on the ground,
outside the reactor building."

120
00:09:59,350 --> 00:10:01,185
Smooth, black mineral, graphite.

121
00:10:01,269 --> 00:10:03,104
There's graphite on the ground.

122
00:10:06,065 --> 00:10:09,068
Well, there was a tank explosion.
There's debris.

123
00:10:09,443 --> 00:10:10,611
Of what importance that could be...

124
00:10:10,695 --> 00:10:14,282
There's only one place in the entire
facility where you will find graphite.

125
00:10:14,365 --> 00:10:15,449
Inside the core.

126
00:10:15,533 --> 00:10:17,201
If there's graphite
on the ground outside,

127
00:10:17,285 --> 00:10:19,453
it means it wasn't
a control system tank that exploded.

128
00:10:19,537 --> 00:10:21,831
It was the reactor core. It's open!
(INHALES SHARPLY)

129
00:10:25,126 --> 00:10:26,127
Um...

130
00:10:26,836 --> 00:10:27,920
Comrade Shcherbina?

131
00:10:28,004 --> 00:10:29,964
Comrade General Secretary,
I can assure you

132
00:10:30,047 --> 00:10:31,549
that Professor Legasov is mistaken.

133
00:10:32,133 --> 00:10:34,468
Bryukhanov reports that
the reactor core is intact.

134
00:10:34,635 --> 00:10:37,054
-And as for the radiation...
-Yes, 3.6 roentgen,

135
00:10:37,138 --> 00:10:39,599
which, by the way, is not
the equivalent of one chest X-ray,

136
00:10:39,682 --> 00:10:41,976
but rather 400 chest X-rays.

137
00:10:42,059 --> 00:10:44,395
That number's been bothering me
for a different reason, though.

138
00:10:44,896 --> 00:10:48,232
It's also the maximum reading
on low-limit dosimeters.

139
00:10:48,316 --> 00:10:50,401
They gave us the number they had.

140
00:10:51,235 --> 00:10:54,030
I think the true number
is much, much higher.

141
00:10:54,113 --> 00:10:56,699
If I'm right, this fireman
was holding the equivalent

142
00:10:56,782 --> 00:10:59,243
of four million chest X-rays
in his hand.

143
00:10:59,327 --> 00:11:01,621
Professor Legasov, there's no place
for alarmist hysteria...

144
00:11:01,704 --> 00:11:03,164
It's not alarmist if it's a fact!

145
00:11:03,247 --> 00:11:05,625
Well, I don't hear any facts at all.

146
00:11:06,834 --> 00:11:09,462
All I hear is a man I don't know

147
00:11:09,545 --> 00:11:12,632
engaging in conjecture
in direct contradiction

148
00:11:12,715 --> 00:11:14,717
to what has been reported
by party officials.

149
00:11:15,051 --> 00:11:17,178
I'm, uh... I apologize.

150
00:11:18,262 --> 00:11:20,222
I didn't mean, uh...

151
00:11:20,890 --> 00:11:24,477
(CLEARS THROAT)
Please, may I express my concern

152
00:11:24,560 --> 00:11:27,980
as calmly and as respectfully as I...

153
00:11:28,064 --> 00:11:30,775
<i>-Professor Legasov...
-GORBACHEV: Boris.</i>

154
00:11:31,734 --> 00:11:32,777
I will allow it.

155
00:11:42,495 --> 00:11:43,829
LEGASOV: Um...

156
00:11:45,957 --> 00:11:47,708
An RBMK reactor

157
00:11:48,709 --> 00:11:52,338
uses uranium-235 as fuel.

158
00:11:53,506 --> 00:11:57,468
Every atom of U-235 is like a bullet

159
00:11:58,135 --> 00:12:00,262
traveling at nearly
the speed of light,

160
00:12:00,513 --> 00:12:02,682
penetrating everything in its path,

161
00:12:02,765 --> 00:12:04,850
woods, metal, concrete, flesh.

162
00:12:06,268 --> 00:12:09,230
Every gram of U-235 holds

163
00:12:09,313 --> 00:12:12,274
over a billion trillion
of these bullets.

164
00:12:12,358 --> 00:12:13,901
That's in one gram.

165
00:12:13,985 --> 00:12:16,988
Now, Chernobyl holds
over three million grams,

166
00:12:17,071 --> 00:12:18,531
and right now, it is on fire.

167
00:12:19,991 --> 00:12:24,120
Winds will carry radioactive particles
across the entire continent,

168
00:12:24,578 --> 00:12:26,163
rain will bring them down on us.

169
00:12:26,247 --> 00:12:29,375
That's three million
billion trillion bullets

170
00:12:29,458 --> 00:12:32,920
in the... (SIGHS)
In the air we breathe,

171
00:12:33,337 --> 00:12:35,840
the water we drink, the food we eat.

172
00:12:38,426 --> 00:12:41,804
Most of these bullets
will not stop firing for 100 years.

173
00:12:42,888 --> 00:12:45,891
Some of them, not for 50,000 years.

174
00:12:46,183 --> 00:12:48,894
(CLEARS THROAT) Yes, and this concern

175
00:12:50,021 --> 00:12:53,524
stems entirely from
the description of a rock?

176
00:12:58,237 --> 00:12:59,238
Yes.

177
00:13:01,907 --> 00:13:02,908
Hmm.

178
00:13:06,454 --> 00:13:07,455
Comrade Shcherbina...

179
00:13:09,123 --> 00:13:10,833
I want you to go to Chernobyl.

180
00:13:11,709 --> 00:13:13,669
You take a look at the reactor,
you personally,

181
00:13:13,919 --> 00:13:15,796
and you report directly back to me.

182
00:13:16,005 --> 00:13:18,257
A wise decision,
comrade General Secretary...

183
00:13:18,340 --> 00:13:19,967
And take Professor Legasov with you.

184
00:13:21,677 --> 00:13:22,970
SHCHERBINA: Uh... (CHUCKLES)

185
00:13:23,304 --> 00:13:26,223
Forgive me, comrade
General Secretary, but ...

186
00:13:26,307 --> 00:13:28,267
Do you know how
a nuclear reactor works?

187
00:13:30,728 --> 00:13:32,063
-No.
-GORBACHEV: No.

188
00:13:32,146 --> 00:13:34,106
Well, then how will you know
what you're looking at?

189
00:13:35,483 --> 00:13:36,650
Meeting adjourned.

190
00:13:55,836 --> 00:13:57,838
(HELICOPTER BLADES WHIRRING)

191
00:14:36,460 --> 00:14:38,045
How does a nuclear reactor work?

192
00:14:38,129 --> 00:14:40,381
-What?
-SHCHERBINA: It's a simple question.

193
00:14:42,383 --> 00:14:44,260
It's hardly a simple answer.

194
00:14:44,343 --> 00:14:47,596
Of course, you presume
I'm too stupid to understand.

195
00:14:48,430 --> 00:14:51,725
So I'll restate.
Tell me how a nuclear reactor works,

196
00:14:51,809 --> 00:14:54,353
or I'll have one of these soldiers
throw you out of the helicopter.

197
00:15:04,864 --> 00:15:08,200
A nuclear reactor makes
electricity with steam.

198
00:15:08,742 --> 00:15:11,662
The steam turns a turbine
which generates electricity.

199
00:15:12,079 --> 00:15:13,622
Where a typical power plant

200
00:15:14,165 --> 00:15:15,958
makes steam by burning coal,

201
00:15:16,333 --> 00:15:18,002
a nuclear plant...

202
00:15:23,549 --> 00:15:27,595
In a nuclear plant,
we use something called fission.

203
00:15:29,221 --> 00:15:33,893
We take an unstable element
like uranium-235,

204
00:15:34,643 --> 00:15:36,645
which has too many neutrons.

205
00:15:36,729 --> 00:15:38,647
-A neutron is, uh...
-The bullet.

206
00:15:41,025 --> 00:15:42,693
Yes, the bullet.

207
00:15:43,819 --> 00:15:46,655
So, bullets are flying off
of uranium.

208
00:15:46,739 --> 00:15:47,740
Now,

209
00:15:47,823 --> 00:15:52,453
if we put enough uranium atoms
close together,

210
00:15:53,329 --> 00:15:56,749
the bullets from one atom
will eventually strike another atom.

211
00:15:57,625 --> 00:16:00,669
The force of this impact
splits that atom apart,

212
00:16:00,753 --> 00:16:03,839
releasing a tremendous
amount of energy, fission.

213
00:16:04,215 --> 00:16:06,842
-And the graphite?
-Ah... Yes.

214
00:16:07,176 --> 00:16:11,013
The neutrons are actually traveling
so fast, we call this "flux."

215
00:16:11,388 --> 00:16:13,891
It's relatively unlikely
that the uranium atoms

216
00:16:14,016 --> 00:16:15,267
will ever hit one another.

217
00:16:16,101 --> 00:16:20,773
In RBMK reactors, we surround
the fuel rods with graphite

218
00:16:20,856 --> 00:16:25,027
to moderate, slow down,
the neutron flux.

219
00:16:29,073 --> 00:16:30,115
Good.

220
00:16:31,075 --> 00:16:33,369
I know how a nuclear reactor works.

221
00:16:35,579 --> 00:16:36,997
Now I don't need you.

222
00:16:47,216 --> 00:16:49,093
(BUSY CHATTER)

223
00:16:50,803 --> 00:16:52,388
(PATIENTS COUGHING)

224
00:16:56,850 --> 00:16:58,686
Can you help me?
I need to find my husband.

225
00:16:58,769 --> 00:16:59,812
No. Not now.

226
00:17:04,275 --> 00:17:05,484
-Mikhail!
-Lyudmilla.

227
00:17:05,567 --> 00:17:07,194
-(BABY CRYING)
-Take her.

228
00:17:07,528 --> 00:17:09,280
Take her away from here, please.

229
00:17:09,363 --> 00:17:12,032
Get away from them!
You want to get sick? Go!

230
00:17:12,199 --> 00:17:13,492
Please take her, please take her.

231
00:17:13,575 --> 00:17:14,910
Please take her, please.

232
00:17:14,994 --> 00:17:17,121
Please! Please!

233
00:17:17,454 --> 00:17:19,039
Please take her!

234
00:17:23,127 --> 00:17:24,253
Um...

235
00:17:24,753 --> 00:17:27,339
Excuse me,
I am VASILY Ignatenko's wife.

236
00:17:27,673 --> 00:17:29,925
He's a fireman. Ignatenko.

237
00:17:31,677 --> 00:17:34,346
Ignatenko, Sixth Paramilitary
Fire and Rescue Unit.

238
00:17:34,430 --> 00:17:36,724
I need to find him. Please.

239
00:17:40,644 --> 00:17:42,104
MAJOR BUROV: Ignatenko...

240
00:17:42,187 --> 00:17:44,398
He's being transported
by helicopter to Moscow.

241
00:17:44,898 --> 00:17:46,025
Hospital number six.

242
00:17:46,567 --> 00:17:48,652
Why, is he all right? Can I see him?

243
00:17:48,736 --> 00:17:50,112
You want to see him? Go to Moscow.

244
00:17:50,571 --> 00:17:52,239
But they're not letting us leave here.

245
00:17:55,242 --> 00:17:56,702
Tell them Major Burov allows it.

246
00:17:58,954 --> 00:18:00,456
When are they taking him?

247
00:18:01,332 --> 00:18:02,333
MAJOR BUROV: Now.

248
00:18:04,918 --> 00:18:06,337
(INDISTINCT SHOUTING)

249
00:18:33,238 --> 00:18:34,656
We're approaching the power plant.

250
00:18:36,075 --> 00:18:37,743
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

251
00:18:41,038 --> 00:18:42,247
LEGASOV: What have they done?

252
00:18:44,041 --> 00:18:45,209
Can you see inside?

253
00:18:45,626 --> 00:18:46,835
I don't have to.

254
00:18:48,003 --> 00:18:50,839
Look. That's graphite on the roof.

255
00:18:50,923 --> 00:18:53,092
The whole building's been blown open.

256
00:18:53,175 --> 00:18:54,551
The core's exposed!

257
00:18:54,635 --> 00:18:56,512
I can't see how you can
tell that from here.

258
00:18:56,595 --> 00:18:58,972
For God's sakes. Look at that glow!

259
00:18:59,598 --> 00:19:02,142
That's radiation ionizing the air!

260
00:19:02,351 --> 00:19:04,061
Well, if we can't see, we don't know.

261
00:19:04,311 --> 00:19:05,562
Get us directly over the building!

262
00:19:05,646 --> 00:19:07,064
-Boris...
-Don't use my name!

263
00:19:07,147 --> 00:19:09,691
If we fly directly over an open
reactor, we'll be dead within a week!

264
00:19:09,775 --> 00:19:10,818
Dead!

265
00:19:12,319 --> 00:19:13,404
Sir?

266
00:19:13,487 --> 00:19:16,323
Get us over that building,
or I'll have you shot!

267
00:19:20,828 --> 00:19:22,746
If you fly directly over that core,
I promise you,

268
00:19:22,830 --> 00:19:24,540
by tomorrow morning,
you'll be begging for that bullet.

269
00:19:32,131 --> 00:19:33,257
(LEGASOV GRUNTS)

270
00:20:09,585 --> 00:20:11,211
(MUFFLED CONVERSATION)

271
00:20:13,213 --> 00:20:14,923
Perhaps if you came back another day.

272
00:20:20,220 --> 00:20:21,722
Just wonderful.

273
00:20:22,806 --> 00:20:24,391
KHOMYUK: Deputy Secretary Garanin.

274
00:20:25,601 --> 00:20:29,313
Ulana Khomyuk of the Byelorussian
Institute for Nuclear Energy.

275
00:20:29,480 --> 00:20:30,481
What a pleasure.

276
00:20:30,898 --> 00:20:33,025
-Let me introduce...
-I'm here about Chernobyl.

277
00:20:35,777 --> 00:20:36,987
Such a lovely time.

278
00:20:37,654 --> 00:20:39,907
-Visit again, soon.
-CHULKOV: I will. Thank you.

279
00:20:40,365 --> 00:20:42,534
(DOOR OPENS AND CLOSES)

280
00:20:52,836 --> 00:20:55,589
GARANIN: I must tell you,
this is why no one likes scientists.

281
00:20:56,381 --> 00:20:58,467
When we have a disease to cure,
where are they?

282
00:20:58,800 --> 00:21:02,179
In a lab, noses in their books,
and so Grandma dies.

283
00:21:02,804 --> 00:21:05,307
But when there isn't a problem,
they're everywhere, spreading fear.

284
00:21:05,390 --> 00:21:06,808
I know about Chernobyl.

285
00:21:06,892 --> 00:21:08,060
Oh?

286
00:21:08,143 --> 00:21:10,979
I know that the core is either
partially or completely exposed.

287
00:21:11,063 --> 00:21:13,398
-Whatever that means.
-And that if you don't immediately

288
00:21:13,482 --> 00:21:16,193
issue iodine tablets
and then evacuate this city,

289
00:21:16,276 --> 00:21:18,529
hundreds of thousands of people
are going to get cancer,

290
00:21:18,946 --> 00:21:20,697
and God knows how many more will die.

291
00:21:21,240 --> 00:21:22,282
Yes, very good.

292
00:21:23,075 --> 00:21:25,202
There has been
an accident at Chernobyl,

293
00:21:25,285 --> 00:21:27,079
but I've been assured
there is no problem.

294
00:21:27,412 --> 00:21:28,914
I'm telling you that there is.

295
00:21:29,456 --> 00:21:31,083
I prefer my opinion to yours.

296
00:21:31,875 --> 00:21:33,669
I'm a nuclear physicist.

297
00:21:34,920 --> 00:21:37,923
Before you were Deputy Secretary,
you worked in a shoe factory.

298
00:21:39,424 --> 00:21:42,052
Yes, I worked in a shoe factory.

299
00:21:43,887 --> 00:21:45,138
And now, I'm in charge.

300
00:21:48,267 --> 00:21:49,768
"To the workers of the world."

301
00:21:51,228 --> 00:21:52,813
(GARANIN GULPING)

302
00:22:12,791 --> 00:22:17,504
Stable iodine will keep your thyroid
from absorbing radioactive iodine.

303
00:22:19,006 --> 00:22:21,091
Take one a day
for as long as they last.

304
00:22:21,883 --> 00:22:23,010
And go east.

305
00:22:23,969 --> 00:22:25,596
Get as far from Minsk as you can.

306
00:22:30,267 --> 00:22:32,269
(DOOR OPENS AND CLOSES)

307
00:22:50,037 --> 00:22:51,955
(AIRCRAFT WHIRRING NEARBY)

308
00:22:59,880 --> 00:23:00,881
FOMIN: It's overkill.

309
00:23:01,423 --> 00:23:03,550
Pikalov's showing off
to make us look bad.

310
00:23:03,634 --> 00:23:05,677
It doesn't matter how it looks.

311
00:23:06,470 --> 00:23:08,263
Shcherbina is a pure bureaucrat,

312
00:23:08,847 --> 00:23:10,849
as stupid as he is pigheaded.

313
00:23:11,391 --> 00:23:13,352
We'll tell him the truth
in the simplest terms possible.

314
00:23:13,435 --> 00:23:14,645
We'll be fine.

315
00:23:18,190 --> 00:23:19,191
Pikalov!

316
00:23:45,592 --> 00:23:48,261
Comrade Shcherbina,
Chief Engineer Fomin,

317
00:23:48,345 --> 00:23:51,556
Colonel General Pikalov and I
are honored at your arrival.

318
00:23:51,640 --> 00:23:52,974
Deeply, deeply honored.

319
00:23:53,266 --> 00:23:56,228
Naturally, we regret
the circumstances of your visit,

320
00:23:56,311 --> 00:23:58,355
but, as you can see,
we are making excellent progress

321
00:23:58,438 --> 00:24:00,023
in containing the damage.

322
00:24:00,107 --> 00:24:05,112
We have begun our own inquiry
into the cause of the accident,

323
00:24:05,195 --> 00:24:08,240
and I have a list of individuals

324
00:24:08,323 --> 00:24:10,575
who we believe are accountable.

325
00:24:33,473 --> 00:24:34,891
Professor Legasov, I understand

326
00:24:34,975 --> 00:24:37,269
you've been saying dangerous things.

327
00:24:37,352 --> 00:24:38,729
FOMIN: Very dangerous things.

328
00:24:39,104 --> 00:24:41,022
Apparently, our reactor core exploded.

329
00:24:42,107 --> 00:24:45,986
Please, tell me how
an RBMK reactor core explodes.

330
00:24:48,363 --> 00:24:50,407
I'm not prepared to explain it
at this time.

331
00:24:51,158 --> 00:24:53,535
As I presumed, he has no answer.

332
00:24:53,618 --> 00:24:55,912
It's disgraceful, really.

333
00:24:56,788 --> 00:24:59,374
To spread disinformation
at a time like this.

334
00:25:05,881 --> 00:25:08,216
Why did I see graphite on the roof?

335
00:25:09,176 --> 00:25:10,802
Graphite is only found in the core,

336
00:25:10,886 --> 00:25:13,805
where it's used as
a neutron flux moderator.

337
00:25:14,306 --> 00:25:15,348
Correct?

338
00:25:16,683 --> 00:25:20,228
Fomin, why did the Deputy Chairman
see graphite on the roof?

339
00:25:21,313 --> 00:25:22,689
Well, that can't be.

340
00:25:24,065 --> 00:25:26,735
Comrade Shcherbina,
my apologies, but graphite...

341
00:25:26,943 --> 00:25:27,986
That's not possible.

342
00:25:28,153 --> 00:25:30,238
Perhaps you saw burnt concrete.

343
00:25:30,322 --> 00:25:31,656
Now there you made a mistake,

344
00:25:32,282 --> 00:25:34,701
because I may not know much
about nuclear reactors,

345
00:25:35,160 --> 00:25:36,453
but I know a lot about concrete.

346
00:25:37,412 --> 00:25:39,790
-Comrade, I assure you...
-I understand.

347
00:25:40,665 --> 00:25:42,334
You think Legasov is wrong?

348
00:25:43,585 --> 00:25:44,795
How shall we prove it?

349
00:25:46,797 --> 00:25:48,965
Our high-range dosimeter just arrived.

350
00:25:50,091 --> 00:25:52,302
We could cover one of our trucks
with lead shielding,

351
00:25:53,136 --> 00:25:54,763
mount the dosimeter on the front.

352
00:26:01,311 --> 00:26:03,980
Have one of your men
get as close to the fire as he can.

353
00:26:04,648 --> 00:26:06,316
Give him every bit
of protection you have.

354
00:26:06,399 --> 00:26:09,903
But understand that even with
lead shielding, it may not be enough.

355
00:26:12,405 --> 00:26:13,573
Then I'll do it myself.

356
00:26:19,037 --> 00:26:20,038
Good.

357
00:27:54,299 --> 00:27:56,384
(MUFFLED CONVERSATIONS)

358
00:28:18,782 --> 00:28:19,824
He's back.

359
00:28:49,562 --> 00:28:50,730
It's not three roentgen.

360
00:28:51,564 --> 00:28:52,565
It's 15,000.

361
00:28:53,942 --> 00:28:55,235
BRYUKHANOV: Comrade Shcherbina...

362
00:28:56,403 --> 00:28:57,904
What does that number mean?

363
00:28:57,988 --> 00:28:59,906
It means the core is open.

364
00:29:00,615 --> 00:29:02,742
It means the fire
we're watching with our own eyes

365
00:29:02,826 --> 00:29:04,369
is giving off nearly
twice the radiation

366
00:29:04,452 --> 00:29:06,204
released by the bomb in Hiroshima.

367
00:29:06,287 --> 00:29:08,123
And that's every single hour.

368
00:29:08,206 --> 00:29:11,167
Hour after hour,
20 hours since the explosion,

369
00:29:11,251 --> 00:29:12,877
so 40 bombs' worth by now.

370
00:29:13,128 --> 00:29:14,295
Forty-eight more tomorrow.

371
00:29:14,587 --> 00:29:17,132
And it will not stop.
Not in a week, not in a month.

372
00:29:17,215 --> 00:29:18,758
It will burn and spread its poison

373
00:29:18,842 --> 00:29:20,927
until the entire continent is dead.

374
00:29:24,764 --> 00:29:26,975
Please escort Comrades
Bryukhanov and Fomin

375
00:29:27,058 --> 00:29:28,601
to the local party headquarters.

376
00:29:29,436 --> 00:29:30,895
-Thank you for your service.
-Comrade...

377
00:29:30,979 --> 00:29:32,147
You're excused.

378
00:29:33,023 --> 00:29:34,649
Dyatlov was in charge.

379
00:29:36,276 --> 00:29:37,569
It was Dyatlov!

380
00:29:38,028 --> 00:29:40,613
-Tell me how to put it out.
-We'll use helicopters.

381
00:29:40,864 --> 00:29:42,449
We'll drop water on it
like a forest fire.

382
00:29:42,532 --> 00:29:45,243
No, no, no. You don't understand.
This isn't a fire.

383
00:29:46,161 --> 00:29:50,081
This is a fissioning reactor core
burning at over 2,000 degrees.

384
00:29:50,165 --> 00:29:51,875
The heat will instantly
vaporize the water...

385
00:29:51,958 --> 00:29:53,168
How do we put it out?

386
00:29:53,668 --> 00:29:54,878
(SIGHS HEAVILY)

387
00:29:56,421 --> 00:29:58,423
You are dealing with something

388
00:29:58,506 --> 00:30:02,427
that has never occurred
on this planet before.

389
00:30:04,929 --> 00:30:05,930
Boron.

390
00:30:07,474 --> 00:30:08,933
Boron and sand.

391
00:30:09,851 --> 00:30:12,395
Well, that'll create problems
of its own,

392
00:30:12,479 --> 00:30:14,189
but I don't see any other way.

393
00:30:14,939 --> 00:30:16,733
Of course, it's going to take
thousands of drops,

394
00:30:16,816 --> 00:30:19,402
because you can't fly the helicopters
directly over the core,

395
00:30:19,486 --> 00:30:21,071
so most of it is going to miss.

396
00:30:21,154 --> 00:30:23,323
-How much sand and boron?
-Well, I can't be...

397
00:30:23,406 --> 00:30:26,743
-For God's sake, roughly!
-Five thousand tons.

398
00:30:27,535 --> 00:30:30,288
And obviously, we're going to need
to evacuate an enormous area...

399
00:30:30,371 --> 00:30:31,998
Never mind that. Focus on the fire.

400
00:30:32,082 --> 00:30:34,125
I am focusing on the fire.

401
00:30:34,751 --> 00:30:38,129
The wind,
it's carrying all that smoke.

402
00:30:39,172 --> 00:30:40,715
All that radiation.

403
00:30:41,132 --> 00:30:43,968
At least evacuate Pripyat.
It's three kilometers away.

404
00:30:44,052 --> 00:30:46,096
-That's my decision to make.
-Then make it.

405
00:30:46,179 --> 00:30:48,890
-I've been told not to.
-Is it or is not your decision?

406
00:30:48,973 --> 00:30:50,141
I'm in charge here!

407
00:30:50,767 --> 00:30:52,393
This will go much easier
if you talk to me

408
00:30:52,477 --> 00:30:53,770
about the things you do understand

409
00:30:53,853 --> 00:30:55,939
and not about the things
you do not understand.

410
00:31:00,443 --> 00:31:01,736
Where are you going?

411
00:31:01,820 --> 00:31:05,031
SHCHERBINA: I'm going to get you
5,000 tons of sand and boron.

412
00:31:13,498 --> 00:31:14,749
There's a hotel.

413
00:31:42,152 --> 00:31:43,528
(PHONE RINGS)

414
00:31:43,611 --> 00:31:45,029
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

415
00:32:00,170 --> 00:32:01,963
(MUSIC PLAYING OVER RADIO)

416
00:32:11,472 --> 00:32:12,724
I'd prefer one of those.

417
00:32:21,524 --> 00:32:23,109
WOMAN: Superstitious?

418
00:32:32,202 --> 00:32:33,912
Moscow?

419
00:32:37,415 --> 00:32:39,292
Are you here because of the fire?

420
00:32:40,752 --> 00:32:42,003
(SIGHS SOFTLY)

421
00:32:44,172 --> 00:32:46,591
Anything we should be worried about?

422
00:32:50,678 --> 00:32:51,763
(SIGHS)

423
00:32:51,846 --> 00:32:52,889
No.

424
00:32:53,223 --> 00:32:54,224
(CHUCKLES LIGHTLY)

425
00:33:00,980 --> 00:33:01,981
(GLASS TAPS)

426
00:33:36,975 --> 00:33:38,518
(TREES RUSTLING)

427
00:33:43,564 --> 00:33:45,692
(HELICOPTER BLADES WHIRRING)

428
00:33:53,283 --> 00:33:55,368
(INDISTINCT RADIO CHATTER)

429
00:33:58,413 --> 00:34:00,999
PILOT: (OVER RADIO) We're in position.
Approaching drop.

430
00:34:02,333 --> 00:34:03,668
STASIUK: (OVER RADIO)
Clear to proceed.

431
00:34:05,628 --> 00:34:08,840
PILOT: Copy.
We'll go one by one in rotation.

432
00:34:14,012 --> 00:34:15,805
Remind them about the perimeter.

433
00:34:19,559 --> 00:34:21,686
They cannot fly
directly over the fire.

434
00:34:21,769 --> 00:34:24,188
A minimum of a ten-meter perimeter.

435
00:34:24,272 --> 00:34:25,481
PILOT: Ten-meter perimeter. Copy.

436
00:34:25,815 --> 00:34:29,360
Lead One, per pre-flight,
maintain minimum ten-meter perimeter.

437
00:34:29,902 --> 00:34:30,945
LEAD ONE: Copy that.

438
00:34:31,029 --> 00:34:34,532
Forty meters, 35, 30...

439
00:34:35,700 --> 00:34:37,535
(RADIO STATIC CRACKLING)

440
00:34:38,536 --> 00:34:39,537
LEGASOV: No, no, no.

441
00:34:39,620 --> 00:34:41,372
They're too close.

442
00:34:41,456 --> 00:34:43,207
If they can't get over the fire,
how are they supposed...

443
00:34:43,291 --> 00:34:44,834
The wind will have to carry it.

444
00:34:44,917 --> 00:34:47,545
Tell them,
they cannot go over the core.

445
00:34:50,173 --> 00:34:51,382
STASIUK: Lead One is too close.

446
00:34:51,466 --> 00:34:53,885
I repeat, they are too close.

447
00:34:53,968 --> 00:34:55,219
PILOT: Copy.

448
00:34:56,054 --> 00:34:58,181
Lead One,
you are inside the perimeter.

449
00:34:59,015 --> 00:35:02,268
LEAD ONE: Did not copy.
Signal's breaking up.

450
00:35:04,062 --> 00:35:05,104
PILOT: Lead One?

451
00:35:06,564 --> 00:35:07,565
Do you copy?

452
00:35:08,524 --> 00:35:09,901
Lead One, do you copy?

453
00:35:10,902 --> 00:35:12,779
Lead One, come in.

454
00:35:12,862 --> 00:35:14,614
Do you copy, Lead One?

455
00:35:14,697 --> 00:35:15,865
Lead One!

456
00:35:18,242 --> 00:35:20,161
(HELICOPTER ENGINE WHINES)

457
00:35:25,124 --> 00:35:26,709
(DISTANT CLANGING)

458
00:35:34,425 --> 00:35:36,552
STASIUK: Sir?
What do I tell the others?

459
00:35:39,263 --> 00:35:41,182
Is there any other way, Legasov?

460
00:35:49,774 --> 00:35:50,942
Send the next one in.

461
00:35:53,152 --> 00:35:54,737
Tell them to approach from the west.

462
00:35:55,905 --> 00:35:58,991
STASIUK: Lead Two,
approach from the west.

463
00:36:17,718 --> 00:36:19,554
(PHONE RINGING)

464
00:36:20,304 --> 00:36:22,265
MARINA:
Kurchatov Institute Laboratory Four.

465
00:36:23,015 --> 00:36:26,727
KHOMYUK: Marina Gruzinskaya,
it's Ulana Khomyuk from Minsk.

466
00:36:29,272 --> 00:36:30,273
MARINA: Oh, yes.

467
00:36:30,356 --> 00:36:32,900
How nice of you to phone.
It's been too long.

468
00:36:32,984 --> 00:36:34,110
It has.

469
00:36:34,193 --> 00:36:36,821
I was actually calling
about our friend.

470
00:36:36,904 --> 00:36:39,157
-You know, the one in the country.
-Oh, yes, of course.

471
00:36:39,240 --> 00:36:42,785
I wanted to see how he's doing.
It's so hot there right now.

472
00:36:42,869 --> 00:36:45,329
Yes, it's extremely hot,

473
00:36:45,413 --> 00:36:46,914
but his nephews are flying down,

474
00:36:46,998 --> 00:36:48,916
and they always bring cool weather.

475
00:36:49,000 --> 00:36:50,418
Oh, which nephews?

476
00:36:51,586 --> 00:36:54,839
Simka, who's 14,
and little Boris, who's five.

477
00:36:55,381 --> 00:36:56,757
Well that's wonderful.

478
00:36:56,841 --> 00:36:58,718
Though children can
make you even hotter

479
00:36:58,801 --> 00:37:00,386
when they're crawling all over you.

480
00:37:00,470 --> 00:37:01,721
Maybe I should visit them.

481
00:37:01,804 --> 00:37:03,931
No, they don't want visitors.

482
00:37:04,015 --> 00:37:06,100
I'm sorry, um,
I have to get back to work.

483
00:37:06,184 --> 00:37:08,102
It's very busy right now. Goodbye.

484
00:37:11,481 --> 00:37:13,816
They're dropping sand
and boron on the fire.

485
00:37:15,026 --> 00:37:16,110
It's what I would do.

486
00:37:18,237 --> 00:37:20,072
Yes, I'm sure it is.

487
00:37:42,428 --> 00:37:43,638
Where are you going?

488
00:37:44,722 --> 00:37:45,723
Chernobyl.

489
00:37:46,974 --> 00:37:47,975
(DOOR OPENS)

490
00:37:51,270 --> 00:37:53,231
(DOOR OPENS, CLOSES)

491
00:37:54,065 --> 00:37:56,901
It's been smooth. Twenty drops.

492
00:37:56,984 --> 00:37:58,861
(HELICOPTER WHIRRING NEARBY)

493
00:38:02,573 --> 00:38:04,158
What?

494
00:38:06,744 --> 00:38:10,414
(SIGHS) There are 50,000 people
in this city.

495
00:38:10,498 --> 00:38:11,624
(SIGHS)

496
00:38:11,707 --> 00:38:15,002
Professor ll yin,
who's also on the commission,

497
00:38:15,086 --> 00:38:17,922
says the radiation isn't
high enough to evacuate.

498
00:38:18,005 --> 00:38:20,174
Ii yin isn't a physicist.

499
00:38:20,258 --> 00:38:22,760
Well, he's a medical doctor.
If he says it's safe, it's safe.

500
00:38:22,843 --> 00:38:25,346
-Not if they stay here.
-We're staying here.

501
00:38:25,429 --> 00:38:28,766
Yes, we are, and we'll be dead
in five years.

502
00:38:37,608 --> 00:38:39,986
I'm sorry, I...

503
00:38:40,069 --> 00:38:41,654
I'm sorry.

504
00:39:02,633 --> 00:39:04,343
(PHONE RINGING)

505
00:39:20,109 --> 00:39:22,194
-Shcherbina.
-(MAN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

506
00:39:32,622 --> 00:39:33,873
Thank you.

507
00:39:40,546 --> 00:39:44,342
A nuclear plant in Sweden
has detected radiation

508
00:39:44,425 --> 00:39:47,470
and identified it
as a by-product of our fuel.

509
00:39:48,596 --> 00:39:50,973
The Americans took satellite photos.

510
00:39:52,350 --> 00:39:55,519
The reactor building,
the smoke, the fire.

511
00:39:55,895 --> 00:39:57,063
(SIGHS)

512
00:39:58,064 --> 00:39:59,774
The whole world knows.

513
00:40:06,781 --> 00:40:08,866
The wind has been blowing
toward Germany.

514
00:40:10,826 --> 00:40:13,162
They're not letting
children play outside

515
00:40:15,206 --> 00:40:16,666
in Frankfurt.

516
00:40:28,427 --> 00:40:29,470
Want a smoke?

517
00:40:45,861 --> 00:40:48,406
NEWSCASTER: There has been a nuclear
accident in the Soviet Union

518
00:40:48,489 --> 00:40:50,282
and the Soviets
have admitted that it happened.

519
00:40:50,366 --> 00:40:51,742
The Soviet version is this,

520
00:40:51,867 --> 00:40:53,369
One of the atomic reactors

521
00:40:53,452 --> 00:40:56,706
at the Chernobyl Atomic Power Plant
near the city of Kiev was damaged,

522
00:40:56,789 --> 00:40:58,624
and there is speculation in Moscow

523
00:40:58,708 --> 00:41:01,127
that people were injured
and may have died.

524
00:41:01,210 --> 00:41:04,130
The Soviets may have been fairly quick
to acknowledge the accident

525
00:41:04,213 --> 00:41:07,550
because evidence in the form
of mild nuclear radiation

526
00:41:07,633 --> 00:41:11,095
had already reached beyond
the Soviet borders to Scandinavia.

527
00:41:44,754 --> 00:41:48,215
(WOMAN CALLING FOR ATTENTION
IN RUSSIAN OVER MEGAPHONE)

528
00:41:53,053 --> 00:41:55,347
(WOMAN ANNOUNCING IN RUSSIAN
OVER MEGAPHONE)

529
00:42:27,838 --> 00:42:29,965
(WOMAN CONTINUES ANNOUNCING
OVER MEGAPHONE)

530
00:43:00,287 --> 00:43:01,914
(INAUDIBLE)

531
00:43:17,680 --> 00:43:19,056
(GIRL CRYING)

532
00:43:30,734 --> 00:43:32,903
(ANNOUNCEMENT CONTINUES
OVER MEGAPHONE)

533
00:43:53,591 --> 00:43:55,467
(INAUDIBLE)

534
00:44:15,613 --> 00:44:18,282
(ANNOUNCEMENT REPEATING
OVER MEGAPHONE)

535
00:44:23,829 --> 00:44:26,040
(SIREN WAILING)

536
00:45:26,266 --> 00:45:29,186
I said turn around.
This is a restricted zone.

537
00:45:29,269 --> 00:45:31,563
I'm from the Byelorussian
Institute for Nuclear Energy.

538
00:45:31,647 --> 00:45:33,190
Do you have permission?

539
00:45:33,273 --> 00:45:35,776
Listen to me, I need to speak
to someone urgently.

540
00:45:35,859 --> 00:45:37,069
Turn around right now,

541
00:45:37,152 --> 00:45:38,195
or I'll arrest you.

542
00:45:38,278 --> 00:45:42,116
If you arrest me, you should take me
to the highest possible authority.

543
00:45:46,704 --> 00:45:49,248
LEGASOV: We have to start
a radio logical survey.

544
00:45:49,331 --> 00:45:53,002
Sector by sector, on foot,
dosimeters in hand.

545
00:45:54,962 --> 00:45:56,338
Are you all right?

546
00:45:59,133 --> 00:46:00,467
Of course.

547
00:46:00,551 --> 00:46:01,844
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACH)

548
00:46:01,927 --> 00:46:06,098
Comrades... The guards arrested
this woman at the south checkpoint.

549
00:46:06,181 --> 00:46:07,766
I'd have put her in a cell...

550
00:46:07,850 --> 00:46:10,185
But he thought you should
know that I know.

551
00:46:10,269 --> 00:46:12,229
I know that
your reactor core is exposed.

552
00:46:12,312 --> 00:46:15,065
I know the graphite's on fire,
the fuel is melting,

553
00:46:15,149 --> 00:46:17,276
and you're dropping
sand and boron on it,

554
00:46:17,359 --> 00:46:20,279
which you probably thought was
smart, but you've made a mistake.

555
00:46:20,362 --> 00:46:23,699
Ulana Yuriyvna Khomyuk,
Chief Physicist,

556
00:46:23,782 --> 00:46:25,993
Byelorussian Institute
for Nuclear Energy.

557
00:46:26,076 --> 00:46:29,496
And you are
Valery Alexeyevich Legasov?

558
00:46:29,580 --> 00:46:31,915
Smothering the core
will put the fire out,

559
00:46:31,999 --> 00:46:34,877
but the temperature will
eventually increase...

560
00:46:34,960 --> 00:46:36,503
LEGASOV: Believe me,
I'm perfectly aware.

561
00:46:36,587 --> 00:46:38,630
But I estimate at least a month

562
00:46:38,714 --> 00:46:40,549
before it melts through
the lower concrete pad,

563
00:46:40,632 --> 00:46:41,759
-which gives us time...
-KHOMYUK: No.

564
00:46:41,842 --> 00:46:44,219
You don't have a month.
You have approximately two days.

565
00:46:45,345 --> 00:46:46,513
Yes,

566
00:46:46,597 --> 00:46:48,599
the fuel would take a month

567
00:46:48,682 --> 00:46:50,684
to reach the concrete pad here.

568
00:46:51,143 --> 00:46:52,144
But first...

569
00:46:53,562 --> 00:46:56,774
it's going to burn through
the biological shield here by Tuesday.

570
00:46:56,857 --> 00:46:58,317
And when it does,

571
00:46:58,400 --> 00:47:01,320
it's going to hit these tanks,
bubbler pools, reservoirs...

572
00:47:01,403 --> 00:47:04,281
Reservoirs for the ECS.
I understand your concern,

573
00:47:04,364 --> 00:47:06,492
but I confirmed it
with plant personnel.

574
00:47:06,575 --> 00:47:08,869
-The tanks are nearly empty.
-No, they were nearly empty.

575
00:47:10,120 --> 00:47:12,956
Each of these points here, here,

576
00:47:13,040 --> 00:47:15,667
and here all drain
to the bubbler pools.

577
00:47:15,751 --> 00:47:18,420
I'm guessing that every pipe
in the building ruptured.

578
00:47:18,504 --> 00:47:21,548
And then there are those fire engines
that I saw on the way in.

579
00:47:21,632 --> 00:47:23,717
The fire hoses are still connected.

580
00:47:24,468 --> 00:47:27,179
They've been gushing water
into the structure this whole time.

581
00:47:27,262 --> 00:47:28,555
The tanks are full.

582
00:47:30,057 --> 00:47:32,392
(SIGHS) The tanks are full.

583
00:47:34,686 --> 00:47:35,771
(SIGHS)

584
00:47:35,854 --> 00:47:38,565
(IN RUSSIAN) From the Council
of Ministers of the USSR.

585
00:47:38,899 --> 00:47:43,362
An accident has occurred
at Chernobyl Nuclear Power Station.

586
00:47:43,445 --> 00:47:46,657
One of the nuclear reactors
has been damaged.

587
00:47:46,740 --> 00:47:50,410
Measures are being taken to address
the consequences of the accident.

588
00:47:50,494 --> 00:47:53,122
Victims are receiving assistance.

589
00:47:53,205 --> 00:47:55,874
A government commission
has been formed.

590
00:48:02,047 --> 00:48:03,340
(DOOR OPENS)

591
00:48:12,266 --> 00:48:16,478
I have 10 minutes,
then I'm back on the phone

592
00:48:16,562 --> 00:48:19,481
apologizing to our friends,

593
00:48:19,565 --> 00:48:21,942
apologizing to our enemies.

594
00:48:23,026 --> 00:48:26,280
Our power comes
from the perception of our power.

595
00:48:26,947 --> 00:48:29,992
Do you understand
the damage this has done?

596
00:48:30,075 --> 00:48:32,119
Do you understand what's at stake?

597
00:48:34,454 --> 00:48:35,706
Boris.

598
00:48:38,250 --> 00:48:42,171
Professor Legasov
will deliver our briefing.

599
00:48:44,381 --> 00:48:45,924
There is some good news.

600
00:48:46,008 --> 00:48:48,719
The air drops are working
to douse the fire.

601
00:48:48,802 --> 00:48:52,598
There's been a reduction
in radionuclide emissions,

602
00:48:52,681 --> 00:48:56,768
but the fire will not be extinguished
for at least another two weeks.

603
00:48:59,313 --> 00:49:02,649
There is also an additional problem.

604
00:49:03,734 --> 00:49:05,569
Nuclear fuel doesn't turn cold

605
00:49:05,652 --> 00:49:08,363
simply because it is not on fire.

606
00:49:08,447 --> 00:49:09,740
In fact, the temperature
will likely rise

607
00:49:09,823 --> 00:49:12,743
as a result of the blanket of sand
we've dropped.

608
00:49:12,826 --> 00:49:15,662
The uranium will melt the sand,

609
00:49:15,746 --> 00:49:17,623
creating a kind of lava

610
00:49:17,706 --> 00:49:20,834
which will begin to melt down
through the shield below.

611
00:49:20,918 --> 00:49:22,586
You have made lava?

612
00:49:24,796 --> 00:49:26,757
I anticipated this.

613
00:49:28,800 --> 00:49:33,222
I believed there was time to reinforce
this lower concrete pad

614
00:49:33,305 --> 00:49:36,433
before the lava reached the Earth
and contaminated the groundwater.

615
00:49:36,516 --> 00:49:39,645
But as it turned out, I was
worried about the wrong thing.

616
00:49:39,728 --> 00:49:41,438
Uh...

617
00:49:41,521 --> 00:49:45,067
It was my understanding
that these large water tanks

618
00:49:45,150 --> 00:49:47,861
under the reactor
were essentially empty.

619
00:49:47,945 --> 00:49:51,031
This is Ulana Khomyuk
of the Byelorussian Institute.

620
00:49:51,114 --> 00:49:53,283
Thanks to her insight,
we are now aware

621
00:49:53,367 --> 00:49:56,828
that the tanks are, in fact, full.

622
00:49:56,912 --> 00:50:00,457
Of water.
Why is that a problem, Professor?

623
00:50:01,667 --> 00:50:02,918
(KHOMYUK CLEARS THROAT)

624
00:50:04,795 --> 00:50:06,588
When the lava enters these tanks,

625
00:50:06,672 --> 00:50:09,091
it will instantly
super heat and vaporize

626
00:50:09,174 --> 00:50:12,844
approximately 7,000
cubic meters of water,

627
00:50:12,928 --> 00:50:16,306
causing a significant
thermal explosion.

628
00:50:17,015 --> 00:50:18,642
How significant?

629
00:50:18,725 --> 00:50:22,479
We estimate
between two and four megatons.

630
00:50:22,938 --> 00:50:25,524
Everything within
a 30-kilometer radius

631
00:50:25,607 --> 00:50:27,526
will be completely destroyed,

632
00:50:27,609 --> 00:50:30,988
including the three remaining
reactors at Chernobyl.

633
00:50:31,071 --> 00:50:34,449
The entirety of the radioactive
material in all of the cores

634
00:50:34,533 --> 00:50:37,744
will be ejected at force

635
00:50:37,828 --> 00:50:39,871
and dispersed by a massive shock wave,

636
00:50:41,081 --> 00:50:43,208
which will extend

637
00:50:43,292 --> 00:50:46,128
approximately 200 kilometers

638
00:50:46,211 --> 00:50:49,256
and likely be fatal
to the entire population of Kiev

639
00:50:49,339 --> 00:50:51,133
as well as a portion of Minsk.

640
00:50:51,717 --> 00:50:54,553
The release of radiation
will be severe

641
00:50:54,636 --> 00:50:56,179
and will impact

642
00:50:56,263 --> 00:51:00,517
all of Soviet Ukraine,
Latvia, Lithuania,

643
00:51:00,600 --> 00:51:05,022
Byelorussia, as well as Poland,
Czechoslovakia, Hungary,

644
00:51:05,105 --> 00:51:07,399
Romania, and most of East Germany.

645
00:51:11,278 --> 00:51:14,072
What do you mean "impact?"

646
00:51:15,073 --> 00:51:17,659
For much of the area,
a nearly permanent disruption

647
00:51:17,743 --> 00:51:19,453
of the food and water supply,

648
00:51:20,537 --> 00:51:23,373
a steep increase in the rates
of cancer and birth defects.

649
00:51:23,457 --> 00:51:25,959
I don't know how many deaths
there will be, but many.

650
00:51:26,877 --> 00:51:28,712
For Byelorussia and the Ukraine,

651
00:51:28,795 --> 00:51:31,465
"impact" means
completely uninhabitable

652
00:51:31,548 --> 00:51:34,051
for a minimum of 100 years.

653
00:51:38,555 --> 00:51:41,892
There are more than 50 million people

654
00:51:41,975 --> 00:51:44,686
living in Byelorussia and Ukraine.

655
00:51:44,770 --> 00:51:46,730
Sixty, yes.

656
00:51:51,068 --> 00:51:52,819
And how long before this happens?

657
00:51:53,320 --> 00:51:55,697
Approximately 48 to 72 hours.

658
00:52:00,452 --> 00:52:02,704
But we may have a solution.

659
00:52:02,788 --> 00:52:04,748
We can pump the water from the tanks.

660
00:52:04,831 --> 00:52:08,001
Unfortunately, the tanks are
sealed shut by a sluice gate,

661
00:52:08,085 --> 00:52:09,711
and the gate can only be opened

662
00:52:09,795 --> 00:52:11,755
manually from within
the duct system itself.

663
00:52:11,838 --> 00:52:15,133
So, we need to find
three plant workers

664
00:52:15,217 --> 00:52:17,636
who know the facility well enough
to enter the basement,

665
00:52:17,719 --> 00:52:22,557
here, find their way through
all these duct ways,

666
00:52:22,641 --> 00:52:25,018
get to the sluice gate valve here,

667
00:52:25,102 --> 00:52:29,356
and give us the access we need
to pump out the tanks.

668
00:52:29,689 --> 00:52:32,317
Of course, we will need
your permission.

669
00:52:32,609 --> 00:52:34,444
My permission for what?

670
00:52:34,528 --> 00:52:37,114
LEGASOV: Uh, the water in these ducts,

671
00:52:37,197 --> 00:52:39,991
the level of
radioactive contamination...

672
00:52:40,075 --> 00:52:41,868
They'll likely be dead in a week.

673
00:52:44,204 --> 00:52:47,749
We're asking for your permission
to kill three men.

674
00:52:55,882 --> 00:52:57,551
Well...

675
00:52:57,634 --> 00:53:00,804
Comrade Legasov, (CLEARS THROAT)

676
00:53:00,887 --> 00:53:03,557
All victories inevitably
come at a cost.

677
00:53:58,612 --> 00:54:00,697
(WATER DRIPPING)

678
00:54:29,184 --> 00:54:32,229
And open the sluice gate valve, here.

679
00:54:33,021 --> 00:54:37,025
The valve will be difficult
to operate, so we'll need three men

680
00:54:37,108 --> 00:54:40,695
who will need to know
the basement layout.

681
00:54:40,779 --> 00:54:44,574
And, of course, any volunteers
will be rewarded.

682
00:54:45,075 --> 00:54:48,411
A yearly stipend of 400 rubles.

683
00:54:55,377 --> 00:55:00,131
And, uh, for those of you working
in reactors one and two, promotions.

684
00:55:00,215 --> 00:55:04,010
(CLEARS THROAT) Why are reactors
one and two still operating at all?

685
00:55:04,553 --> 00:55:07,847
My friend was a security guard
that night, and, uh, she's now dying.

686
00:55:08,431 --> 00:55:10,684
And we've all heard about the firemen.

687
00:55:10,767 --> 00:55:14,729
And now you want us to swim
underneath a burning reactor?

688
00:55:15,397 --> 00:55:17,440
Do you even know
how contaminated it is?

689
00:55:18,149 --> 00:55:19,150
(CLEARS THROAT)

690
00:55:19,776 --> 00:55:21,611
I don't have an exact number.

691
00:55:21,695 --> 00:55:24,906
You don't need an exact number
to know if it will kill us.

692
00:55:24,990 --> 00:55:26,241
But you can't even tell us that.

693
00:55:28,368 --> 00:55:30,704
Why should we do this?
For what, 400 rubles?

694
00:55:30,787 --> 00:55:32,414
(SOFT MURMURING)

695
00:55:34,332 --> 00:55:36,459
You'll do it because it must be done.

696
00:55:41,631 --> 00:55:44,175
You'll do it because nobody else can.

697
00:55:47,304 --> 00:55:50,890
And if you don't, millions will die.

698
00:55:52,142 --> 00:55:54,477
If you tell me that's not enough,
I won't believe you.

699
00:55:56,313 --> 00:56:00,442
This is what has always
set our people apart.

700
00:56:00,525 --> 00:56:03,445
A thousand years of sacrifice
in our veins.

701
00:56:04,487 --> 00:56:06,948
And every generation
must know its own suffering.

702
00:56:07,991 --> 00:56:11,077
I spit on the people who did this,

703
00:56:11,161 --> 00:56:13,079
and I curse the price I have to pay.

704
00:56:16,207 --> 00:56:20,170
But I'm making my peace with I,
now you make yours.

705
00:56:20,712 --> 00:56:22,380
And go into that water.

706
00:56:24,924 --> 00:56:26,760
Because it must be done.

707
00:56:43,902 --> 00:56:45,362
Ananenko.

708
00:56:49,699 --> 00:56:51,159
Bezpalov.

709
00:56:56,122 --> 00:56:57,791
Baranov.

710
00:57:29,698 --> 00:57:31,491
(HELICOPTER WHIRRING NEARBY)

711
00:58:57,619 --> 00:58:59,037
(DOOR SHUTS)

712
00:59:02,957 --> 00:59:04,417
(MUFFLED GRUNTING)

713
00:59:08,129 --> 00:59:10,131
(DOSIMETER CRACKLING)

714
01:00:00,348 --> 01:00:02,475
(DOSIMETER CONTINUES CRACKLING)

715
01:00:17,073 --> 01:00:18,074
(MUFFLED GRUNT)

716
01:00:45,560 --> 01:00:47,604
(DOSIMETER'S CRACKLING GROWS LOUDER)

717
01:01:07,540 --> 01:01:09,292
(WATER SLOSHING)

718
01:01:12,629 --> 01:01:14,672
-(RAPID CRACKLING)
(MUFFLED GASP)

719
01:01:15,423 --> 01:01:17,133
(WATER GUSHING)

720
01:01:19,093 --> 01:01:20,970
(GRUNTS URGENTLY)

721
01:01:27,143 --> 01:01:28,144
(GRUNTS)

722
01:01:31,981 --> 01:01:33,858
(ALL PANTING)

723
01:01:40,239 --> 01:01:41,240
(MUFFLED GRUNT)

724
01:01:42,617 --> 01:01:44,410
(WORRIED GRUNT)

725
01:01:44,494 --> 01:01:46,496
(DOSIMETER CRACKLING
LOUDLY AND RAPIDLY)

726
01:01:46,996 --> 01:01:48,289
(TAPPING)

727
01:01:58,925 --> 01:02:01,177
-(PANTING)
(URGENT TAPPING)

728
01:02:01,260 --> 01:02:03,346
(LOUD AND RAPID CRACKLING CONTINUES)

729
01:02:05,181 --> 01:02:07,892
(RAPID AND HEAVY BREATHING)

